#X text 530 224 coefficient;
#X text 160 40 The filter equation is: yn = yn[-1] + k * (xn - yn[-1]). Inside the filter \, the coefficient value is clipped from 0 to 1 \, by the way., f 63;
#X text 160 82 The frequency input is then converted to the 'k' coefficient. For values <= 50 we have the radians per sample (w) \, which is a good approximation and just like [lop~] works. For values above we have: k = sqrt(((2 - cos(w))ˆ2) - 1) + cos(w) - 1 as the formula., f 63;
#X text 160 144 By the default \, the argument and right inlet is frequency in hz \, but you can set the object to take the 'k' coefficient input directly., f 63;
